{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656649"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18754"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18754"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.13,0.07,0.77,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77344"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11486"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10518"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26592"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77344"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring periods of dehydration, the kidneys must conserve water by producing concentrated urine. Urea plays an important role in this process.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of urea recycling in the kidney?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreases sodium reabsorption","Stimulates aldosterone release","Promotes potassium secretion","Increases medullary osmotic gradient","Reduces blood pressure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that urea recycling \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreases medullary osmotic gradient\u003C/strong\u003E. As water is reabsorbed from the collecting duct under the influence of antidiuretic hormone, urea becomes concentrated in the tubular fluid. Some of this concentrated urea is reabsorbed into the medullary interstitium, contributing to the high osmolality that drives water reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases sodium reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E - Urea recycling does not directly affect sodium transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes potassium secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Urea recycling is not involved in potassium handling\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Urea recycling helps concentrate urine but does not directly affect blood pressure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates aldosterone release\u003C/strong\u003E - Urea recycling does not influence hormone production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process is particularly important during dehydration when the kidney needs to conserve water by producing concentrated urine. The high urea concentration in the medulla helps maintain the osmotic gradient needed for water reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urea is reabsorbed from the collecting duct during dehydration to help concentrate urine.","Urea recycling in the medulla helps maintain the osmotic gradient needed for water reabsorption.","The concentration of urea in the medullary interstitium increases as water is reabsorbed."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18754"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62851"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T16:41:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T16:42:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11486"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77344"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"},"relationsh